INSTITUTE FOR STRATEGIC LINGUISTIC COMPLIANCE (ISLC)
White Paper No. 48-C
“Coping Strategies for Users Trapped in Narrative Superposition: How to Maintain Sanity When Everything Is Simultaneously World-Changing and Slightly Better Than Grammarly.”
Classification: Public / Mildly Concerned but Productive

⸻

1. Executive Summary

This white paper addresses the growing psychological condition affecting knowledge workers, developers, researchers, and individuals who have heard the phrase “This changes everything” more than twelve times in a fiscal quarter.

The condition, formally recognized by the Institute as Narrative Superposition Exposure Syndrome (NSES), occurs when a user is simultaneously exposed to the following mutually incompatible claims:
	•	Artificial Intelligence will replace all human labor.
	•	Artificial Intelligence cannot reliably count letters in “strawberry.”
	•	Artificial Intelligence is an existential risk.
	•	Artificial Intelligence is a helpful email assistant.
	•	Artificial Intelligence is the new electricity.
	•	Artificial Intelligence is slightly better than Grammarly.

This produces a cognitive state known as Reality Bifurcation Fatigue (RBF), in which the user must hold two beliefs at once:
	1.	The world is about to change completely.
	2.	The main use is still writing emails and code.

The purpose of this paper is to provide structured coping mechanisms so that users may continue functioning in professional environments where every software update is described as historic, transformational, and mostly a UI redesign.

