3. Coping Strategies for Affected Users

3.1 The Altitude Adjustment Technique (AAT)

Users are advised to convert all executive statements into Practical Altitude Equivalents (PAE) using the following chart:

Executive Statement	Translation
“This changes everything.”	“You can draft emails faster.”
“AGI is near.”	“It writes decent Python.”
“This will disrupt all industries.”	“It summarizes meetings.”
“This is a new form of intelligence.”	“It formats bullet points.”
“We surpassed AGI.”	“It remembers your chat history sometimes.”

This translation process reduces Narrative Altitude Sickness (NAS).

3.2 The Sanity Preservation Workflow (SPW)

The Institute recommends the following daily routine:
	1.	Read one AI announcement.
	2.	Wait 24 hours.
	3.	Open the actual tool.
	4.	Attempt a real task.
	5.	Observe that the main benefit is time saved on annoying tasks.
	6.	Experience emotional stabilization.

This process is known as Expectation Grounding Through Mild Disappointment (EGMD).

3.3 The Grammarly Benchmark Rule (GBR)

To maintain psychological equilibrium, users should apply the Grammarly Benchmark Test:

If the primary daily use overlaps with what Grammarly, Stack Overflow, and Excel already did, you are not witnessing the singularity. You are witnessing workflow optimization.

This rule has been shown to reduce Imminent Robot Apocalypse Anxiety (IRAA) by up to 63%.

3.4 The Narrative Noise Filter (NNF)

Users should classify AI news into three categories:

Category	Description	Action
World-Changing	Investors talking	Ignore
Industry-Changing	Executives talking	Wait
Actually Useful	Engineers shipping features	Use

This filtering system is called Signal Extraction From Hype Environments (SEHE).

